@samrad tokens are not stored in the backend, that's one of the pros of using JWT for authentication, so they help build a stateless API. A normal workflow might be to store the token in the browser's localstorage or sessionstorage. "Logging out" would just mean removing the token from the client and that's it.

You might want to read a bit more on [authentication with JSON Web Tokens](http://jpadilla.com/search/jwt).

For now, to include anything additional in the response you'll have to implement a custom view yourself.

The deprecation warnings are a nuisance, so +1 here.

Another consideration: it would be better to check what path to take at import time, rather than re-checking it during each call.

For example, something like this at the top of the file could replace the current checks.

```
from django import VERSION as DJANGO_VERSION

if DJANGO_VERSION < (1, 10):
    def _is_authenticated(request_user):
        return request_user.is_authenticated()
else:
    def _is_authenticated(request_user):
        return request_user.is_authenticated
```

