Yeah, I think though that this gets at a good question. How prescriptive do we want to be about how users configure their cluster? I like removing the `sudo` option because it makes _everything so much cleaner_, but it makes the assumption that people set up their clusters so that Docker can be run without sudo.

However, to argue with myself, having docker as a dependency is prescriptive in and of itself. Also, it is less of an ask to ask the user to properly configure their system permissions so that they don't need `sudo` to run docker, than to ask sysadmins everywhere to allow people to "abuse" sudo. Anyways, if you _have_ sudo access, you can just set up the groups properly anyways so that you don't need to run docker as root, which I suppose makes this a bit moot.

